March 31, 2025

Monthly Log: March 2025

  • MacStories Team

This month, Devon checks in one year after beginning to use Everlog to create a timeline of his life, and John thinks it’s time to stop hyping or ignoring AI and judge it critically like any other technology.

A Life Timeline Check-In

  • Devon

In the March 2024 edition of the Monthly Log, I wrote about using Everlog to create a timeline of my life with the help of Apple’s journaling suggestions. Here’s how I wrapped up that story:

How cool is it going to be to see a list of today’s entries, including my core workout, the podcast I listened to on my commute, my latest blog post, and the TV show I watched, in a year’s time? I can’t wait to find out.

Well, seeing as it’s been a year since I posed that question, I think it’s time to answer it. After taking this detailed approach to journaling so many aspects of my life over the past year, has it been worth it?

The short answer is a resounding, “Yes,” but there’s more to it than that. Today, I’d like to check in on my journaling workflow one year later: how I’m benefiting from it, what I’ve changed, and how I still think it could improve.

Journaling as Memory

To be honest, when I expanded my journaling practice to incorporate journaling suggestions, I was taking a bit of a spaghetti-at-the-wall approach. I had no way to know for sure if any of the data I was saving would be valuable. Would I actually care about it down the line? Would I even bother to look? And would I be able to keep putting in the time to log all of this stuff in the first place?

Thankfully, my efforts have persisted and paid off for the most part. When I visit the On This Day section of Everlog, I’m greeted not only by journal entries going back three years, but also by a series of entries from a year ago detailing where I went, what I watched and listened to, and anything I published on that day. It’s usually around five entries per day, so it’s a substantial but not overwhelming amount to take in.

These additional entries have meaningfully enhanced the way I revisit past days. I’ve long enjoyed reading my daily recaps and reflections in written form, but now, I have rich entries with maps, cover art, and links to go along with my own writing. These entries help me not just recall my memories of the day but more viscerally relive them – even the smallest detail like the song I discovered on the way to work.

It may not sound like a big deal, but these seemingly minor additions have actually changed my entire mindset around journaling. Before, I was journaling mainly to reflect; the value of the practice was in the way it helped me immediately process my life to achieve clarity and calm. I certainly still use journaling in this way, but now, I also see it as a form of memory. Its value lives on past today. My journal has become less a silo for my thoughts and more a destination for documenting and remembering my life.

Opening Everlog to revisit past journal entries is now a regular part of my morning routine, and one that I greatly look forward to. I love diving deep into where I was a year ago to remember moments with my loved ones, recall details I might have forgotten, and see the ways my life has changed. As cheesy as it might sound, I truly believe this habit is helping me become a more reflective, realized person.

One practical way this has played out is with exercise. I’ve logged 171 entries in my Workouts journal so far, which is fewer than one per day (or even five per week) since I started recording workouts in Everlog. It’s a part of my life I haven’t been as consistent about as I’d like. Looking back on workouts from a year ago is a good reminder that fitness can be a part of my routine if I choose for it to be. Rather than beating myself up, though, I’m using those old entries as inspiration to get back into exercise and look for ways I can integrate it into my schedule now.

For transparency’s sake, I should say that I am feeling particularly nostalgic at the moment because the time period I’m revisiting in my year-ago journal entries includes my son’s early life. There are a lot of his “firsts” documented in those entries – his first trip to the beach, his first time eating solid food, and more – which I find particularly delightful to reminisce on. It’s made the extra details in my journal even more of a joy to take in.

That is certainly a factor in my appreciation for my life timeline in Everlog, but I think I would still be getting a lot out of it even if that weren’t the case. Looking back on my journal entries from previous years, I find myself wishing that I had this level of detail going back further. I’m grateful to know that as I continue this practice into the future, the timeline will continue to grow and become even more valuable to me.

Complementing My Journal

That isn’t to say that I nailed every aspect of it out of the gate, though. When I wrote about my journaling practice last year, the part I was least sure about was saving photos. Apple’s journaling suggestions system offers up pictures it thinks you’ll want to save to your journal, but the more I used it, the less useful I found the system’s suggestions to be. It just didn’t seem to do a good job of picking out the photos I wanted to keep the most.

And really, I didn’t want to have to choose which pictures to save and which to discard. I already curate my iCloud photo library, so why would I choose to further narrow it down in my journal? Something about saving photos in multiple places just didn’t sit right with me, either.

I ended up deleting my Photos journal and leaving that category out of Everlog entirely. What I really wanted was a way to easily revisit all of the photos and videos from my library taken on a particular date in previous years – On This Day, but for photos. It was a simple idea, but one that I found difficult to put into practice.

Everlog doesn’t offer a feature like this, though I think it would be an excellent and natural addition to the app’s existing On This Day feature. Apple’s Photos app also, curiously, doesn’t include such a section. The app will generate On This Day memory videos from time to time, but I haven’t found a way to access this sort of view every day on demand.

The solution I found is a free app called Photos On This Day by Kyle Coburn. It offers an overview of every photo taken on the current date in previous years, as well as the ability to open any picture in a detail view and select other dates on a calendar. The app also includes a Home Screen widget showing one photo from a past year, which I keep in my Today View. The app isn’t perfect – it can’t play videos and has trouble reconciling locally-stored photos with their cloud versions – but it does what I was looking for, so it’s become a part of my morning routine alongside Everlog.

Another app that’s come into my life over the last year is Collections by Matteo D’Ignazio. In the two-part series I wrote about the app for Club MacStories members last year, I mentioned that one way I use it is as a Creativity Log. I save everything I publish online to a database in Collections for future reference. But I document my creative work in Everlog, too. Why save the same information in two places?

While having a record of what I share online in Everlog is handy for quick recollection, it isn’t as useful as an actual reference. In Collections, I’m able to save all sorts of metadata about the things I publish, as well as the actual contents of blog posts and episode show notes. That makes it easy for me to look up old work and quantify my output in a way that simply wouldn’t make sense in Everlog. So rather than bog down my journal with data that doesn’t belong there, I’m piggybacking off my journaling habit and duplicating that information in a more actionable way in Collections to get the best of both worlds.

I’m doing the same for TV shows and movies that I watch. All of that information goes straight from my media tracker Sequel into my journal each day, but it also gets copied into a database in Collections for running numbers. I like to think of this dual approach as both qualitative and quantitative, two sides of the same coin.

While I originally conceived of Everlog as my single go-to place for my life timeline, complementing it with Photos On This Day and Collections has made the whole thing more complete. What started as a journal has grown into so much more.

What’s Missing?

There are ways that I’d like to improve my approach to journaling, but the limitations mostly haven’t changed since last year. Like the Journal app itself, journaling suggestions continue to be limited to the iPhone. I do most of my journaling on my Vision Pro, so this has resulted in a fractured experience for me. I have to add all of my suggestion-based information from my phone and then switch to the Vision Pro to write up my daily journal entries. I’d prefer it if suggestions could sync between platforms via iCloud; I’d love to give the Journal app a real try, too, but journaling exclusively from my iPhone is a nonstarter.

While journaling suggestions expanded to include third-party apps in iOS 18, I’ve only ever seen two suggestions from non-Apple apps. Interestingly, they were both from Ferrite, a tool I use on my iPad Pro. I guess suggestions can sync between devices after all, just not in a way that we can access.

The TV app still isn’t included as a source for journaling suggestions, so I’ve had to continue to rely on my homemade solution for journaling about shows and films I watch. And paid podcasts also aren’t offered as suggestions, meaning I can’t add members-only shows like Connected Pro to my journal.

I’ve learned to live with these limitations, but based on the fact that both the Journal app and journaling suggestions received meaningful improvements last fall, I’m hoping that we’ll see some of these issues addressed at WWDC. And even with these quirks, the journaling suggestions system is still an amazing resource that I’m grateful Apple allows third-party apps to integrate with.

I am incredibly pleased with the way my approach to journaling has worked out so far. It does take some effort on the front end to get all of the information saved in Everlog, but now that I’m able to revisit my entries after some time has passed, I can confidently say that it’s well worth it. I plan to keep crafting my life timeline going forward and enjoying all of its benefits along the way.

Approaching AI with a Critical Optimist's Eye

  • John

On Friday, Allison Morrow published a story for CNN Business suggesting that Apple’s delay of AI features doesn’t matter because AI isn’t good enough for the sort of consumer products we’re accustomed to from the company. In Morrow’s parlance, Apple isn’t failing AI; AI is failing AI.

She argues that Wall Street’s desire for an iPhone upgrade super cycle pushed Apple to announce Apple Intelligence too early, and now, the tech media is scolding users for not adapting to AI’s imperfections. If that sounds familiar, it‘s because it’s a form of the old “You’re holding it wrong” argument that Steve Jobs was rightly criticized for using during the iPhone 4 Antennagate incident in 2010. Blame the user, not the technology.

I get where Morrow is coming from, but these arguments don’t hold up under scrutiny.

Sure, investors would love for Apple to release a new technology that drives iPhone sales. This isn’t new or novel, nor does it matter whether the technology that fuels a super cycle is AI or something else.

That said, Wall Street certainly understands the potential of Apple Intelligence, especially given Apple’s preference for running it locally on-device. If Apple can ship a compelling suite of AI features, users are going to need all the memory and storage they can get to run models locally. But that’s not unique to AI. Any new technology that pushes the limits of existing hardware will fuel upgrades. Apple’s been doing that for years with its camera systems.

The heart of Morrow’s argument is that the problem lies with the inaccuracy of the large language models, not Apple or its users. She focuses on Apple’s personal context demo from WWDC 2024:

Back in June, Apple floated a compelling scenario for its newfangled Siri. Imagine yourself, frazzled and running late for work, simply saying into your phone: Hey Siri, what time does my mom’s flight land? And is it at JFK or LaGuardia? In theory, Siri could scan your email and texts with your mom and give you an answer. That saves you several annoying steps of opening your email to find the flight number, copying it, then pasting it into Google to find the flight’s status.

In reference to this demo, Morrow declares:

If it is anything less than 100% accurate, it’s useless. Because even if there’s a 2% chance it’s wrong, there’s a 2% chance you’re stranding mom at the airport, and mom will be, rightly, very disappointed. Our moms deserve better!

This quote highlights the wrong turn Apple took at WWDC last year. We now know from Mark Gurman’s reporting at Bloomberg that Apple’s WWDC demo was more aspirational than real. That illustrates why concept videos are a bad idea. Implementing concepts is hard, especially when the technology you plan to rely on makes things up. Steve Jobs popularized the notion that Apple hardware and software “just works,” but how do you do that when AI sometimes doesn’t?

It’s hard to argue with Morrow’s conclusion that inaccuracies in high-stakes requests are unacceptable. The trouble is that the conclusion fails to account for the myriad of low-stakes busywork tasks that AI is very good at today and the fact that Apple has barely scratched the surface with those sorts of tasks, either. AI can generate a searchable, time-stamped transcript from a YouTube video; reformat text; build simple scripts and web apps for analyzing data; compile, source, and summarize your research notes; translate your writing into languages you don’t know; and transcribe your voice in real time with crazy accuracy.

Morrow understands what we should all acknowledge: AI isn’t magic. Silicon Valley’s insistence otherwise is why people get tired of hearing about AI. The Internet has been inundated with breathless fluff about its superpowers. The AI industry is replete with grifters selling AI solutions to simple problems that are more easily solved by existing automation tools and publicly available APIs, something Federico and I discussed on this week’s AppStories+ post-show for AppStories+ subscribers and Club Premier members. But just because AI isn’t as magical as the grifters would like you to believe and current models fail more often than is acceptable in high-stakes situations, that doesn’t mean AI is useless.

The problem with Morrow’s argument is that it goes too far. It’s cynically dismissive of the entire AI industry.

I get how seductive that point of view is. I’ve nearly ended up there myself. But I remain first and foremost optimistic about technology, including AI, despite the many reasons the industry has given me to become a cynic. I don’t expect to ever be fairly compensated for what AI companies took when they trained their models, although I firmly believe that history will judge their actions as the biggest intellectual property heist ever perpetrated. Nor do I expect we’ll see the kind of meaningful AI regulation that I think is necessary, given the political climate in the U.S., Europe, and elsewhere.

Instead of cynicism, the past couple of years of covering AI has taught me something different – to stretch beyond simple optimism to something I think of as critical optimism. Like other technologies, I believe AI has the potential to do a lot of good; the trouble stems from the hype, the grifters, and the potentially enormous downsides of getting AI wrong. Now more than ever, it’s not useful to be blindly optimistic or dismissive of AI. It’s here to stay, and while Morrow is right that our moms deserve better, it’s on us to assess AI with a critical eye and work to steer it in a positive direction, not ignore it.
